Technology Acquisition Assessments for a Scientific Infrastructure Programme
Overview

A national science and engineering organisation was preparing for the next phase of a multi-decade infrastructure programme. With the transition from a completed flagship deliverable into a larger system build, leadership needed to make two high-stakes technology decisions:

Which capabilities to acquire next

How to reduce acquisition risk through structured evaluation, not intuition or vendor influence

An IfM-guided technology acquisition assessment, turning complex technical requirements, market constraints, and organisational readiness into a clear decision framework for leadership.

The Challenge

The programme faced two critical capability gaps.

1) Data infrastructure capability gap

Future operations required moving and storing extreme volumes of data: multi-terabit-per-second transport and hundreds of petabytes per year. In the local context, a complete “standard commercial” solution was unlikely to be available off-the-shelf.

2) Maintenance capability gap for cryogenic systems

Highly sensitive instrumentation relied on cryogenic cooling systems with demanding upkeep. When maintenance capability sits outside the organisation:

turnaround times increase

operational uptime decreases

lifecycle cost rises

These decisions could not be made on reputation, persuasion, or past precedent. They required structured evaluation grounded in readiness, fit, and the organisation’s ability to absorb the capability.

Deep Field Approach

We applied a three-step method aligned to recognised technology acquisition frameworks.

1) Identify the technologies, partners, and maturity

We defined the target technologies and assessed feasible acquisition paths:

Technology 1: Data-Intensive Infrastructure Platform
A scaled capability requiring multi-discipline delivery, likely through a consortium or collaborative delivery model.

Technology 2: Cryogenic O-Level Maintenance Capability
Best approached through enablement and capability transfer with an existing specialist provider.

We assessed maturity using Technology Readiness concepts to clarify expected development effort and integration risk.

2) Evaluate readiness to acquire and operationalise

We evaluated each acquisition through three lenses designed to prevent a common failure mode: buying impressive technology that the organisation cannot integrate, operate, or sustain.

A) Absorptive Capacity
Can the organisation adopt and exploit the capability in practice (skills, routines, internal acceptance, reuse of knowledge)?
Assessed via a structured checklist and weighted scoring.

B) Partner Compatibility
Is the delivery partner (or consortium) compatible in working style, capability, strategic alignment, and prior alliance performance?

C) Technology Suitability
Does the capability fit the organisation’s objectives with feasible access to know-how (know-what / know-how / know-who), manageable technical challenges, and acceptable cost drivers?

3) Convert analysis into decision-ready guidance

We consolidated findings into a leadership-friendly acquisition view:

market readiness vs technology readiness

organisational absorption readiness

partner model suitability

technology fit and constraints

recommended actions to proceed safely into procurement planning

The Two Technology Assessments
Technology 1: Data-Intensive Infrastructure Platform (Future Operations)

This assessment focused on building/acquiring the capability to handle extreme throughput and storage requirements, where system integration is the real challenge: land/power/fibre, cooling, physical and cyber security, operating model, and long-term sustainability.

Key insight
The market need was clear and time-bound, but a complete off-the-shelf solution in the local environment was unlikely. The most realistic path was a collaborative delivery model with structured requirements definition and governance.

Technology 2: Cryogenic O-Level Maintenance Capability (Uptime and Cost)

This assessment addressed uptime risk caused by externalised maintenance, long repair cycles, and expensive OEM turnaround.

Key insight
The technology is mature and operationally proven. The risk sits less in invention and more in capability transfer: local reproducibility of workflow, training under real operating conditions, and sustained in-house enablement.

